4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, an inmate may not attend his
6 or her parole hearing.
7 This bill would allow an inmate to attend his or
8 her parole hearing by telephone, video conference, or
9 any other similar communications system and would
10 provide parameters for the remote parole hearings.
11
12
13 A BILL
14 TO BE ENTITLED
15 AN ACT
16
17 Relating to paroles; to provide that an inmate may
18 attend his or her parole hearing remotely and provide
19 parameters for remote parole hearings.
20 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
21 Section 1. (a)(1) The Board of Pardons and Paroles
22 shall allow an inmate to participate in his or her parole
23 hearing via telephone, video conference, or any other similar
24 communications system that allows the inmate to interact with
25 the members of the Board of Pardons and Paroles. The board
26 shall give the victim, victim's family, and others
27 representing the victim the option to see or hear the inmate's
28 statement.
Page 1

statement.
SB240 INTRODUCED
29 (2) The board shall allow any other individual
30 participating in a parole hearing, including, but not limited
31 to, the victim, the victim's family, a crime victim advocate,
32 a law enforcement officer, or a prosecutor, to participate in
33 a parole hearing via telephone, video conference, or any other
34 similar communications system.
35 (3) An inmate may waive his or her rights provided
36 under this subsection.
37 (b) Unless the victim or the victim's family chooses
38 otherwise, the board shall not allow an inmate to see, hear,
39 or otherwise interact with victims, victims' families, or
40 crime victim advocates who address the board or attend the
41 hearing.
42 (c) If the communications system fails or is in any way
43 interrupted during a hearing, the board shall suspend the
44 hearing until communication is reestablished.
45 (d) The board shall only provide access to the hearing
46 to individuals permitted to speak pursuant to rules
47 established by the board. Individuals authorized to speak may
48 speak by telephone, video conference, or any other similar
49 communications system. The board shall use video conferencing
50 when that communications system is available; otherwise, the
51 board may choose any other authorized communication method.
52 Section 2. This act shall become effective on October
53 1, 2026.
